1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:05,390
In this video we are going to learn event driven architecture in microservices.

2
00:00:06,320 --> 00:00:11,930
In an event driven microservice architecture, services communicate with each other by publishing and

3
00:00:11,930 --> 00:00:13,400
subscribing to events.

4
00:00:14,330 --> 00:00:20,240
When a service needs to communicate with another service, it publishes an event to the message broker

5
00:00:20,240 --> 00:00:21,200
or event bus.

6
00:00:21,650 --> 00:00:28,040
Other services can then subscribe to that event and take appropriate action when the event is received.

7
00:00:28,340 --> 00:00:30,380
This can have several benefits.

8
00:00:30,830 --> 00:00:31,880
For example.

9
00:00:32,060 --> 00:00:33,530
Asynchronous communication.

10
00:00:33,530 --> 00:00:39,380
One key feature of event driven microservice architecture is that it allows services to communicate

11
00:00:39,380 --> 00:00:42,020
asynchronously rather than synchronously.

12
00:00:42,140 --> 00:00:47,900
This means that a service can publish an event and continue processing without waiting for a response

13
00:00:47,900 --> 00:00:49,340
from the other service.

14
00:00:49,970 --> 00:00:52,640
Another benefit is decoupled communication.

15
00:00:53,090 --> 00:00:58,610
And another key feature of event driven microservice architecture is that it decouples the publisher

16
00:00:58,610 --> 00:01:04,250
and subscriber that allowing them evolve independently without affecting each other.

17
00:01:04,400 --> 00:01:10,310
This can make it easier to make changes to individual servers without affecting the rest of the system.

18
00:01:12,590 --> 00:01:15,650
And another benefit could be the real time processing.

19
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:21,740
Event driven architectures can support real time processing as events are published and consumed as

20
00:01:21,740 --> 00:01:22,940
soon as they occur.

21
00:01:23,180 --> 00:01:28,760
This can be useful in such a scenario where you need to react to events in real time.

22
00:01:28,760 --> 00:01:34,280
For example, in systems that use change data capture to track changes to a database.

23
00:01:34,850 --> 00:01:37,460
Another benefit is high volume events.

24
00:01:37,880 --> 00:01:44,000
Event driven architectures are well suited to handling high volume events, as they can scale horizontally

25
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:46,910
by adding more events consumers as needed.

26
00:01:46,940 --> 00:01:53,090
This can be particularly useful in Microsoft's architectures, where individual services can be scaled

27
00:01:53,090 --> 00:01:56,360
independently in order to handle increased load.

